HEADWORD: Ranunculus
<hw>Ra*nun"cu*lus</hw> <pr>(r⟦adot⟧*n⟦ucr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k⟦usl⟧*l⟦ucr⟧s)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>Ranunculuses</plw>
<pr>(r⟦adot⟧*n⟦ucr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k⟦usl⟧*l⟦ucr⟧s*⟦ecr⟧z)</pr>, L.
<plw>Ranunculi</plw> <pr>(-l⟦imac⟧)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a little frog,
a medicinal plant, perhaps crowfoot, dim. of <ets>rana</ets> a frog; cf.
<ets>raccare</ets> to roar.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of
herbs, mostly with yellow flowers, including crowfoot, buttercups, and
the cultivated ranunculi (<spn>Ranunculus Asiaticus</spn>,
<spn>Ranunculus aconitifolius</spn>, etc.) in which the flowers are
double and of various colors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

